| foreign key to a column that already exists | ALTER TABLE table\_name ADD FOREIGN KEY  (column\_name) REFERENCES referenced\_table\_name(referenced\_column\_name); example: ALTER TABLE students ADD FOREIGN KEY (major\_id) REFERENCES majors(major\_id); The **foreign key** is a **column** in a table that is used to associate two tables. Specifically, it references the **primary key** of another table, which creates a link between the two.  The foreign key is on the child table. That is, the child table has a unique\_id column and a foreign key column.  A foreign key is not used on a table with a many to many relationship.  Use a Join table for that. |

| JOIN (INNER JOIN) | Returns only rows that match in both tables. Non-matching rows are excluded from the results. This type of join is the most common and is used when you want to get only the rows where there’s a relationship between the two tables.  |
| FULL JOIN (OUTER JOIN) | all the rows from both tables, even if there is no match between the tables. If there is no match in Table A, the result will still include the row from Table B with NULL values for Table A’s columns. If there is no match in Table B, the result will include the row from Table A with NULL values for Table B’s columns. “Show me everything from Table A, everything from Table B, and match them where possible.”  |

| View 1: many associated tables | same format:SELECT table\_A.column1, table\_B.column2 FROM table\_A FULL JOIN table\_B  ON table\_A.primary\_key \= table\_B.foreign\_key; example:SELECT \* FROM characters JOIN more\_info ON characters.character\_id=more\_info.character.id;  |

| GROUP BY  can use the aggregate functions  | SELECT major\_id FROM students GROUP BY major\_id; SELECT major\_id, COUNT(\*) FROM students GROUP BY major\_id; SELECT major\_id, MIN(gpa) FROM students GROUP BY major\_id; SELECT MIN(gpa) FROM students GROUP BY major\_id;  Using an aggregate function in the select returns a single value and SQL easily associates the single value to the GROUP BY group. However, SQL doesn’t know how to handle multiple values for each GROUP BY group which is why the GROUP BY column must match one of the SELECT columns. SQL raises an error.  SELECT gpa  FROM students GROUP BY major\_id; ERROR:  column "students.gpa" must appear in the GROUP BY clause or be used in an aggregate function SELECT first\_name FROM students GROUP BY major\_id; ERROR:  column "students.first\_name" must appear in the GROUP BY clause or be used in an aggregate function |
| HAVING | SELECT \<column\> FROM \<table\> GROUP BY \<column\> HAVING \<condition\> The condition must be an aggregate function with a test. example: SELECT major\_id, MIN(gpa), MAX(gpa) FROM students GROUP BY major\_id HAVING MAX(gpa) \= 4.0; |
| FULL JOIN | SELECT \* FROM \<left\_table\> FULL JOIN \<right\_table\>  ON \<left\_table\>.\<foreign\_key\_column\> \= \<right\_table\>.\<foreign\_key\_column\>; \* selects all columns from both the left and right tables. Rows that have a match between the two tables are included. Rows that don’t have a match from the left table appear with NULL values for columns from the right table. Rows that don’t have a match from the right table appear with NULL values for columns from the left table. ALL the rows from both tables appear with blank spots if values are missing.  **Most inclusive**: It returns **all rows** from **both tables**, even if there is no match. example:SELECT \* FROM majors FULL JOIN students ON majors.major\_id \= student.major\_id; It's showing all the columns from both tables, the two major\_id columns are the same in each row for the ones that have it. You can see that there are some students without a major, and some majors without any students. | INNER JOIN | SELECT \* FROM \<left\_table\> INNER JOIN \<right\_table\>  ON \<left\_table\>.\<foreign\_key\_column\> \= \<right\_table\>.\<foreign\_key\_column\>; \* selects all columns from both the left and right tables. |  | General Guidelines: Table with primary interest (focus): Typically, you’d prefer the table you care most about or the one that contains the primary information you’re analyzing to be the left table in a LEFT JOIN. In your example, if you’re more interested in majors and you want to find majors that have no students, you would use a LEFT JOIN with majors as the left table. This way, you will get all majors (even those with no students). Data availability: If you expect that the right table might have more data or records, but you still want to make sure all records from the left table appear, you’d use a LEFT JOIN. If you expect that the left table might have missing matches for some rows, and you want to ensure you still include all data from the right table, you’d use a RIGHT JOIN. Clarity of intent: It’s often about clarity of intent. You might want to position the table that you care more about or that drives the analysis as the left table. | USING | Join tables if the foreign key column has the same name in both tables. Here's an  SELECT \* FROM \<table\_1\> FULL JOIN \<table\_2\> USING(\<column\>); Parentheses are required around the column name.  If major\_id is in both tables, it will be combined to one column. Example:  SELECT \* FROM students FULL JOIN majors USING(major\_id); The USING clause can only be applied to **columns that are common** to both tables — meaning the column names and types must be the same in both tables. you can definitely use **multiple columns** in the USING clause if the tables have more than one column in common\! You just need to pass the columns as a **comma-separated list** inside the parentheses. |

\#\!/bin/bash  
\# Info about my computer science students from students database  
echo \-e "\\n\~\~ My Computer Science Students \~\~\\n"  
PSQL\="psql \-X \--username=freecodecamp \--dbname=students \--no-align \--tuples-only \-c"  
echo \-e "\\nFirst name, last name, and GPA of students with a 4.0 GPA:"  
echo "$($PSQL "SELECT first\_name, last\_name, gpa FROM students WHERE gpa \= 4.0;")"  
echo \-e "\\nFirst name, last name, and GPA of students whose last name begins with an 'R' or after and have a GPA greater than 3.8 or less than 2.0:"  
echo "$($PSQL "SELECT first\_name, last\_name, gpa FROM students WHERE last\_name \>= 'R' AND (gpa \> 3.8 OR gpa \< 2.0);")"  
echo \-e "\\nAll course names whose first letter is before 'D' in the alphabet:"  
echo "$($PSQL "SELECT course FROM courses WHERE course \< 'D'")"  
echo \-e "\\nLast name of students whose last name contains a case insensitive 'sa' or have an 'r' as the second to last letter:"  
echo "$($PSQL "SELECT last\_name FROM students WHERE last\_name ILIKE '%sa%' OR last\_name LIKE '%r\_'")"  
echo \-e "\\nFirst name, last name, and GPA of students who have not selected a major and either their first name begins with 'D' or they have a GPA greater than 3.0:"  
echo "$($PSQL "SELECT first\_name, last\_name, gpa FROM students WHERE major\_id IS NULL AND (first\_name LIKE 'D%' OR gpa \> 3.0)")"  
echo \-e "\\nCourse name of the first five courses, in reverse alphabetical order, that have an 'e' as the second letter or end with an 's':"  
echo "$($PSQL "SELECT course FROM courses WHERE (course LIKE '\_e%' OR course LIKE '%s') ORDER BY course DESC LIMIT 5")"  
echo \-e "\\nAverage GPA of all students rounded to two decimal places:"  
echo "$($PSQL "SELECT ROUND(AVG(gpa),2) FROM students")"  
echo \-e "\\nMajor ID, total number of students in a column named 'number\_of\_students', and average GPA rounded to two decimal places in a column name 'average\_gpa', for each major ID in the students table having a student count greater than 1:"  
echo "$($PSQL "SELECT major\_id as major\_id, COUNT(\*) AS number\_of\_students, ROUND(AVG(gpa),2) AS average\_gpa FROM students GROUP BY major\_id HAVING COUNT(\*) \> 1; ")"  
echo \-e "\\nList of majors, in alphabetical order, that either no student is taking or has a student whose first name contains a case insensitive 'ma':"  
echo "$($PSQL "SELECT major FROM majors FULL JOIN students ON majors.major\_id \= students.major\_id WHERE first\_name ILIKE '%ma%' OR first\_name IS NULL ORDER BY major;")"  
echo \-e "\\nList of unique courses, in reverse alphabetical order, that no student or 'Obie Hilpert' is taking:"  
echo "$($PSQL "SELECT DISTINCT(course) FROM students FULL JOIN majors USING(major\_id) FULL JOIN majors\_courses USING (major\_id) FULL JOIN courses USING (course\_id) WHERE last\_name IS NULL OR last\_name \= 'Hilpert' ORDER BY course DESC;")"  
echo \-e "\\nList of courses, in alphabetical order, with only one student enrolled:"  
echo "$($PSQL "SELECT courses.course FROM students FULL JOIN majors USING(major\_id) FULL JOIN majors\_courses USING (major\_id) FULL JOIN courses USING (course\_id)  GROUP BY courses.course HAVING COUNT(students.last\_name) \= 1 ORDER BY course;")"
